==English==

===Verb===
{{en-verb|sucks in|sucking in|sucked in|head=[[suck]] [[in]]}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To [[cause]] someone to become slowly more and more [[involved]] in a business or situation that is often not to that person's liking.
#: ''I really didn't want to be on the committee, but somehow I got '''sucked in'''.''
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To [[contract]] one's [[abdominal]] [[muscle]]s to make one's [[stomach]] look [[flatter]].
#: ''I '''sucked in''' my belly, hoping to hide the extra weight I had put on over the holidays.''

====Usage notes====
* When used in the sense "to cause someone to become involved in a situation", it is usually in the passive; one is '''sucked in''' by the situation.

====Synonyms====
* {{qualifier|cause someone to become involved in a situation:}} [[draw into]], [[draw in]], [[rope in]], [[rope into]], [[suck into]]

